  "doc_id": "3880",
  "text": "Concerning the walk, although the WPG presented here is simplified, its core concepts do not conflict with improvements such as those in [CITATION_1] , which add robustness. Another possible future investigation in WPG design is the addition of the terminal capturability constraint, as indicated in Section IV-C. Apart from improving the WPG itself, its integration in whole-body control can also be improved, with works such as [CITATION_2] , which aims at combining the separate QPs. Finally, a limiting factor in our experiments was the low-level stabilizer of the HRP-4, which modifies the joint references sent to the robot actuators [CITATION_3] . We must devise a dedicated stabilizer, consistent with our framework. Another challenging topic of on-going work consists in applying the multirobot version of our QP controller [CITATION_4] to include the human as an additional \"robot\". However, going beyond simulation [CITATION_5] requires estimation of the human's full or partial pose and inertia parameters, to effectively close the overall control loop in a pHRI setting. Finally, once the system is improved in terms of the performance, user-related studies is also worthy of investigation.",
